description.text:
This is a modular spool holder design in wait for the new Prusa i3 MK3 and their multi material upgrade.

Design is modular so you only have to print out as many legs as you actually need. For the Prusa's 4 material upgrade you will need 5 legs. For all intents and purposes this can be scaled to whichever amount of rolls that you need.

You will also need 30mm rod of any kind (wood is just fine). Make sure you cut one to lengh according to how much space you need between the legs for the spools + the width of each leg + 25mm caps at each end.

Caps are designed to fit tightly and print with 1mm gap. Legs print with 2mm gap for the rod, so it's not too tight but also not too loose.

This holder will easily hold 1KG rolls but it is designed for max 2.3 KG rolls of filament.

Print legs standing and caps laying down on their flat part. Supports will be needed for the rod holes only. Rafts/brims depend on you. Set infill to 25%.

Any ideas and suggestions are very welcomed. Note this is still work in progress and I won't be able to actually print it to show off until my MK3 and the multi material upgrade arrives.

description.text: This is a simple mini servo coupling which connects a "mini series" RC servo to a 4mm rod. I was absolutely happy to see that this insane detail is printed with ease on my Ultimaker! This coupling features a tiny hole for a M2 screw which secures the coupling towards the servo. Another hole is there to fix the rod (where you have to drill a tiny hole into) to the coupling. See a video of the use case as well as more close-up photos here: https://plus.google.com/116416453568555193309/posts/4a1KFqxNY9A I tried different slicers which gave quite different results due to different threshold values for small details I guess. The coupling will be used in a flying object which I will release very soon - ready to print of course! Follow me on Google+ or watch for it on Thingiverse.

• Slice the "Servo_Coupling_v01.stl" with your favorite slicer and see how it performs with tiny details.
  • I used 0.1 mm layers with most slicers.
  • If there's a threshold value for small details, go low... you'll need it.
  • Speedwise: Take it easy, it's a small part anyways.
    • See more pictures of the different slicing results here: https://picasaweb.google.com/116416453568555193309/MiniServoCouplingPrintedOnMyUltimaker# Let me know if you need the source files (Autodesk Inventor). I could upload them after the weekend. Note: The dimensions on the part are not very accurate. It was more a "guessing-process" in order to get a good print with Kisslicer (which I tried first). I needed to increase the measurements in order to make it fit. So the *.stl is based on these values. Just print it and scale it slightly if it's too loose or tight. Happy printing!

description.text:

They can be feathers for a funky peacock,  terrifying tentacle tips, or friendly flippers! It doesn't matter what you use them as, just don't leave without printing out these leaves!   
The OGOBILD attachments are interchangeable, safe, and functional toys you can use to create anything you can imagine. Now you can download, modify, and print out your own custom pieces.

General

I couldn't find a bumper case for my Huawei P8 Lite 2017, so i decided to create my own. Note that this doesn't fit the old P8 Lite, but only the 2017 version. It's a single piece which just gets snapped directly onto the phone. The part shown above was printed in green PLA.

Since it has to be printed with supports, expect a bit of cleaning of the inner surfaces before you can put it onto your phone.

How to fit it onto your phone

See above for photos of the steps described here.

  1. After printing and cleaning, get your phone and insert it with the top end first. Push it as far up as possible.
  2. Next, get the lower right edge of the phone into the bumper. To do this, pull the lower right corner of the frame to the right (until the lower right corner of the phone is almost at the USB cutout) and push it in.
  3. Finally push the lower left corner into the bumper. This might take a bit of force, as the bumper has a very tight fit.
  4. ....
  5. Profit!

PS:
Yes, the shattered screen made me think about getting a bumper in the first place ;)
Feel free to modify, remix or alter this part in any way, just give credit where credit is due.

description.text:
QR Code generator for OpenSCAD

This project can generate OpenSCAD source code for a QR code encoding given value. There are already two projects on Thingiverse, but the first does not work properly and the second requires running executable on your machine. So I created third one.

How it works

This project works completely online in JavaScript. Go to https://ridercz.github.io/OpenSCAD-QR/ and enter the value of your code. The page will generate image of your code (so you can check it's working) and also OpenSCAD code, which will create array with 0 and 1, representing the code.

Also provided is simple OpenSCAD module (method) qr_render for drawing the encoded QR Code with given parameters:

  • module_size - the size of single square, default 1x1 mm
  • height - extrusion height, default 1 mm

The resulting code is not intended to be used 'as is', you are supposed to incorporate it to your own models. For example see the QR Code Dog Tag

Acknowledgements

The heavy lifting - QR Code generation itself - was done by the perfect qrcode-generator by Kazuhiko Arase. I just added OpenSCAD code generation and simple web interface.

description.text: This sliding shade straps to your vehicle's sun visor.  The shade extends to block the sun from your eyes when the visor is not long enough.

The "slide" part can be 3D-printed or milled from 6mm (1/4-inch) sheet stock.  The "back" and "shade" parts can be cut with a laser cutter, water-jet cutter, milling machine, or even made with a band or jig saw and a drill.  They should be made from from 3mm (1/8-inch) sheet stock, preferably dark-tinted translucent polycarbonate.
Assemble the slide to the back with 3mm (1/8-inch) pop rivets (8 of them).  Gently flatten the backs of the rivets so that they don't rip the fabric or vinyl of your sun visor.
Slide the shade into the slot in the side.
Attach the sun shade to your sun visor with zip ties or any strap material up to 15mm (9/16-inch) wide.  The straps pass through the slots in the corners of the assembly.
The zip file contains the parts, assembly, and drawings in native SolidWorks 2009 format.

description.text:
Working up the nerve to use flashed chips and 3rd party ABS in my Uno, I decided to relocate the chip and make an easy to use system. So, here is a chip plug, a chip holder, and a base unit.

Pull the chip from your cartridge and replace with a correctly wired chip plug, and run the wires through the carts filament feed hole at the top of the cart.

Wire a base unit spring clip to the other end of the chip plug wires.

After testing for continuity, Assemble to base unit by gluing the spring clip into the base.

Make another base unit, but wire the spring clip to attach to a resetter or Arduino.

Glue the chip itself into the chip holder.

viola!

title: Compact E3Dv6 Dual blower fan mount

description.text:
This is a compact dual blower fan mount for the E3Dv6 hotend (heatsink) with a quick-remove nozzle for cooling down your prints fast afterwards!

I had been using this fan mount, but the form factor didn't really mesh with my setup.
This mount has the heatbreak and layer fans neatly side-by-side, fastened using a single screw, keeping the width down.

(That's my bidirectional filament runout sensor for the Titan extruder in the pictures, if you were curious.)

If there's interest for different nozzles, let me know! You can also design one yourself, using the existing nozzle mount as a base.

You will need:

  • Two 12V blower fans (50x15mm), as pictured. Cheap on Aliexpress.
  • A loooong 35mm M3 screw (or M4, or anything that'll fit through the 4.5mm diameter hole on the blower fans. Maybe even a zip tie!)
  • A nut for the long screw
  • Optionally, a 10mm M3 screw for securing the nozzle to the fan mount (Though the nozzle should be a press-fit, and it may be safer to have it detach on collision)
  • Optionally, a zip tie for securing the fan mount to the E3Dv6 heatsink (it should be a press-fit)

The third design of an SMT tape holder for PnP applications

With this the third design I have tried to solve the main issues I personanly experienced so far, namely ..

1) Tapes must be easy to replace without disrupting components.

2) The top level of the tape must be the same as the PCB irrespective of component height.

3) They must be easy to make without any glueing that will come loose.

4) An "off" pick should not disrupt components.

5) It should be easy to align new tapes.

6) Its must be possible to change the colours behind the tapes to give optimal vision reliability.

The Spring

I had intended to use plastic from a bottle as a spring, for this there are two screw holes in the bottom of the channel. The plastic is cut into a strip that fits the channel and folded over and into the channel, one from each end, to make the spring.

In practice this was "hard" work so I simply replaced the plastic springs with sponge, this works just as well so far. I also made some blocks to mount my PCB's so the top of the tape and PCB are the same height making camera calibration easy.

OpenScad

Its a very simple OpenScad design that should be customisable.

UPDATE 16. November 2017: Added some more parts and a picture of my planned HEVO.
To get more room for cables and bowden tube I lifted up the top frame. So the changed parts will not get mounted to the L brackets. Instead I use normal M5 screws and hammer nuts. I only reduced the M6 hole in this parts to M5. M6 Screws are not needed anymore.

=====================================================================
I am only planning my new HyperCube Evolution. I like the design very much, but I wait for budget clearance from the finance minister. So I used the provided Excel spreadsheet to calculate the parts and assembled them virtual in OpenScad.
I wanted to know how it would work with a normal lead screw attached with a coupler to the stepper instead of using a stepper with an integrated lead screw.
It worked not so good with the sizes from the spreadsheet and the standard parts.
I have found a way to have a build height of 470mm with a 500mm lead screw.
You need a little bit more Z extrusion length and a new Z axis linear rail bracket.
This bracket prevents that the bed crashes into the motor coupler.
For the 500 mm lead screw with a 470 mm build height you will need Z extrusions with 690 mm length.
In other words: add 20 mm to the length of the Z extrusions calculated by the Spreadsheet and use this part.
Be aware that I have not verified this in reality. As I will put the electronics in a room under the printer I will add some tens of millimeter anyway.

If the height of the rail clamp doesn't fit for you: There is a variable in the beginning of the scad file that allows you to adjust it.

description.text:
I have always been concerned when riding my motorcycle that the following car can't tell when i'm engine braking (decelerating without using my brakes). Until I got a new bike (Fz-09) it was never that large a concern because lifting off the throttle never caused such rapid deceleration. After riding this bike for a week or two though I realized this was goin to be a major problem as this bike you only really hit the brakes when going into a turn or coming to a stop. This seemed like as good a time as any to wire in Led lights to a 3 axis accelerometer and some additional Led lighting. I was adding a fender delete kit so I wired them into the running lights for the plate and was pleasantly surprised by the preformance. I was not however impressed by my mounting options. I found I was left with either the plate (not a great idea and a nightmare to hide the wires) or the rear passenger pegs (not really long enough for the LED strips I had found readily available) I tried the included adhesive strips but discovered that wasn't really going to have much holding power. So I broke out the laptop got on solidWorks and created the exact profile of the passenger pegs withe the light strip. I added a hole so they could be tightened down using a zip tie and tada. They are made from black TPU so they are forgiving and flex as you tighten the zip tie. This also makes them virtually invisible from a distance with the LEDs on. Now cars tend to avoid me as my new lights flash at them every time I decelerate and go nuts when I both brake and decelerate. There is no way someone can claim the didn't see me now!!!

description.text:
This is an Insert replacement for Adidas Sport Sun Glasses.
Those inserts clip inside the sunglasses and provide eyesight correction with appropriate lenses.
I broke the insert in my well used Evil Eye Adidas sun glasses. I used them for several sports; competitive volleyball (indoor and beach), snowboarding, white water kayaking.
After several years of good and frequent use, the nylon insert broke and instead of spending another 60$, I opted to try and print a replacement part.
This is the result. I use those glasses 3 to 4 times a week on the water and on the vball court. Harsh testing environment
Printed using the excellent Materio3D PLA, the first printed insert lasted almost a year - until I got whacked in the face with a paddle during a kayak-polo game, earlier this week. Outch!
I printed a couple of replacement inserts and used the new glasses yesterday in a nice little local class IV creek running at good water level.
The original insert (29x26 SPX) is made from nylon. I did a few tests using Nylon 230 from Taulman, but the material was too flexible and I was concerned I would loose the lenses. I plan to test out with Nylon again in the near future using Taulman 910 Nylon.
The insert has a notch in the middle to clip it to the sunglasses. For misty days, night use or indoor, I simply do not use any tinted lenses on the Evil Eye sunglasses.
The Insert is 3mm thick and the space for the lenses could be tweaked using scale factor in your slicer.

So, I drive for Uber on the weekends, the overnight shift, driving all the "drunkies" home. Well, we all know that "drunkies" tend to also become "barfies" from time to time. The hospital-grade legit vomit bags aren't particularly cheap, but you can't beat the design form of "insert mouth into large open end, you drunk bast*rd", so I wanted to replicate that design on the cheap. The bags I use are from the Dollar Store; they're treat bags for kid's birthdays and such. It's important that they be plastic and not paper, since paper doesn't like alcohol-based puke. It's $1 for 25 of the plastic bags, and the rings use very little filament. The rings are a bit large, so you'll likely need to print them separately, but print time for the base is about 30 minutes, and the insert takes less than 10 minutes. I thought about printing multiple sets vertically, but it seemed like it would give a suboptimal fit of the two pieces, so I opted to stick with printing them individually.

The insert fits into a groove in the base. The bag would be placed through the base and then wrapped over it by a half inch or so, with the groove facing downward toward the bottom of the bag. Then, the insert clips in, pinching the overhanging half inch of bag so that it becomes captive (see closeup picture).

The rings are technically reusable, but after Pukie McPukerson does his business in them, you probably won't want them back, which is why I tried to keep the setup as compact as possible, so you won't think twice about letting Mr. McPukerson take his accomplishment home with him. You'll see in the pictures the side-by-side comparison of a legit hospital vomit bag and the one that I've designed here. The main picture kind of looks like it could be an extra large condominium, so if that's why you're here, sorry to disappoint. Enjoy!

title: Fully Printable Spool Reel Mount for Duplicator i3 Plus / Maker Select Plus
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
A fully 3D-printable spool mount for the Duplicator i3 Plus / Monoprice Maker Select Plus. It uses Emmett's excellent printable Gear Bearings to create a rolling platform for the spool, ensuring a smooth delivery of filament without motion jerks. The mount clips on directly to the top of the Duplicator i3 and requires absolutely no tools or additional components to assemble.

Parts to Print:

  • 4x bearing.stl : A single gear bearing. Make sure it spins smoothly. May take a few prints to get it right.
  • 4x bearing_ring.stl: Place each bearing into one of these rings. Prevents the spool from sliding around or falling over.
  • 4x axle.stl : An axle that fits inside the gear bearings and the brackets, which the bearings revolve around.
  • 2x bracket_left.stl : A bracket for holding the gear bearings, to be placed on the left of the bearing.
  • 2x bracket_right.stl : A bracket for holding the gear bearings, to be placed on the right of the bearing.

A small variation of bracket_left and bracket_right are provided with bracket_hollow. Unlike bracket_left or bracket_right, the axle hole for bracket_hollow goes all the way through the model.

Using bracket_hollow instead of bracket_left / bracket_right a little less safe because the axle could theoretically slip all the way through the model, but can offer additional flexibility in configuration.

Assembly:

  1. Fit each bearing into a ring.
  2. Insert an axle through each bearing.
  3. Take two bearings/axles and insert them into a left bracket.
  4. Bring a right bracket onto the left bracket such that the bearings/axles are enclosed between the brackets.
  5. Repeat steps 2-4 for the other pair, but reverse the direction of the rings.
  6. Snap all four brackets onto the top of the printer, as pictured.

description.text:
The MFJ-269 suffers from being accidentally switched on when in the box. Newer models have had a switch guard added as standard. I don't actually like the design of the official MFJ improvement on the 269B.

My 269 is not the B revision and required improving. I designed two different guards.
